1
00:00:37,567 --> 00:00:41,082
A VERY LONG ENGAGEMENT

2
00:02:07,807 --> 00:02:10,275
Saturday the 6th of January, 191 7,

3
00:02:10,527 --> 00:02:14,406
five condemned soldiers
were escorted to Bouchavesnes

4
00:02:14,567 --> 00:02:16,398
at the Front in the Somme.

5
00:02:23,927 --> 00:02:25,201
Watch out for the wire!

6
00:02:46,167 --> 00:02:49,477
The first,
once cheerful and adventurous,

7
00:02:49,647 --> 00:02:54,357
wore the tag number 21 24.
He was drafted from the Seine area.

8
00:02:55,167 --> 00:02:58,318
On his feet were boots,
taken from a dead German.

9
00:02:58,767 --> 00:03:02,123
Before becoming 21 24,
he was known as Bastoche

10
00:03:02,287 --> 00:03:04,357
and was hooked on a pretty redhead,

11
00:03:04,527 --> 00:03:06,882
a certain Vronique Passavant.

12
00:03:09,967 --> 00:03:11,878
He was a carpenter.

13
00:03:20,887 --> 00:03:24,197
Taking a break from his woodwork,
they'd go for a beer

14
00:03:24,367 --> 00:03:27,086
at Little Louis' bar,
in Golden Hand St.

15
00:03:29,647 --> 00:03:33,003
He'd taken his boots from an enemy
who no longer needed them.

16
00:03:33,167 --> 00:03:37,160
Stuffed with straw or newspaper,

17
00:03:37,367 --> 00:03:39,676
they replaced his old clodhoppers.

18
00:03:51,167 --> 00:03:54,637
He was court-martialed
for self-mutilation.

19
00:03:55,887 --> 00:03:59,163
Gunpowder had been found
on his wounded hand.

20
00:03:59,367 --> 00:04:01,437
He faced the death sentence.

21
00:04:12,087 --> 00:04:13,884
Watch out for the wire!

22
00:04:20,767 --> 00:04:23,486
The second soldier
was tag number 4077,

23
00:04:23,647 --> 00:04:25,478
also from near the Seine.

24
00:04:26,887 --> 00:04:30,482
He was a welder
for the State Railways, in Bagneux.

25
00:04:30,767 --> 00:04:32,837
His name was Francis Gaignard,

26
00:04:33,407 --> 00:04:34,920
nicknamed Six-Sous.

27
00:04:35,727 --> 00:04:39,197
He knew the poor build the canons
of their own destruction,

28
00:04:39,367 --> 00:04:41,597
but it's the rich who sell them.

29
00:04:42,007 --> 00:04:44,282
He tried to explain it to the troops,

30
00:04:44,447 --> 00:04:46,403
but he wasn't a good speaker.

31
00:04:47,087 --> 00:04:49,760
And cheap wine,
poverty's best friend,

32
00:04:49,927 --> 00:04:52,122
deadened the soldiers' eyes,

33
00:04:52,287 --> 00:04:54,960
making it difficult
to get through to them.

34
00:05:37,767 --> 00:05:42,557
Number 1 81 8 was surely the bravest
and the toughest of them all.

35
00:05:42,887 --> 00:05:45,481
He had once
killed a fellow officer...

36
00:05:48,007 --> 00:05:50,157
an officer who kicked the dead.

37
00:05:51,207 --> 00:05:52,196
Get up!

38
00:05:52,367 --> 00:05:53,516
You swines!

39
00:05:54,047 --> 00:05:55,366
You lazy cowards!

40
00:05:56,607 --> 00:05:58,677
You! Get up!

41
00:05:59,887 --> 00:06:02,003
Attack! Attack!

42
00:06:02,727 --> 00:06:04,604
You! Get going!

43
00:06:16,727 --> 00:06:18,001
No one ever found out.

44
00:06:44,247 --> 00:06:47,364
Benot Notre Dame was a farmer
from Dordogne.

45
00:06:47,847 --> 00:06:49,041
One August morning,

46
00:06:49,327 --> 00:06:51,522
they came to get him at his farm

47
00:06:51,687 --> 00:06:53,564
and sent him off on a train.

48
00:07:06,327 --> 00:07:07,680
Watch out for the wire!

49
00:07:09,727 --> 00:07:13,640
The telephone wire is the only link
to the land of the living.

50
00:07:13,807 --> 00:07:17,561
A flimsy wire, their only chance
for President Poincar's pardon.

51
00:07:17,727 --> 00:07:20,036
Even if the only one
to still believe in it

52
00:07:20,207 --> 00:07:24,803
is him.
Number 7328, recruited in Corsica.

53
00:07:24,967 --> 00:07:26,844
Angel Bassignano.

54
00:07:28,367 --> 00:07:30,722
According to all who'd known him,

55
00:07:30,887 --> 00:07:33,321
he was no angel at all.

56
00:07:33,487 --> 00:07:37,241
He was a liar, a cheat, a show-off,

57
00:07:37,407 --> 00:07:39,398
a sneak and a troublemaker.

58
00:07:53,007 --> 00:07:54,156
Before all this,

59
00:07:54,447 --> 00:07:56,438
Tina Lombardi worked as his whore.

60
00:07:56,607 --> 00:08:00,805
He'd received a 5-year sentence for
an affair of either love or honour,

61
00:08:00,967 --> 00:08:02,958
depending on who he was talking to.

62
00:08:03,127 --> 00:08:06,756
lt was, in fact, a conflict
between village pimps.

63
00:08:13,287 --> 00:08:16,802
Summer 1916,
common-law criminals were enlisted

64
00:08:16,967 --> 00:08:20,277
to beef up regiments
melted in the fires at Verdun.

65
00:08:20,447 --> 00:08:21,641
They gave him the choice.

66
00:08:21,847 --> 00:08:23,838
lt's been shitting shells
round here!

67
00:08:24,007 --> 00:08:25,440
No, it's been rather quiet.

68
00:08:26,007 --> 00:08:27,281
Who are those for?

69
00:08:28,327 --> 00:08:31,603
Well, actually...
you'll be attacking tomorrow.

70
00:08:35,527 --> 00:08:37,165
We're getting a head start.

71
00:08:56,007 --> 00:08:57,725
Watch out for the wire!

72
00:09:06,327 --> 00:09:10,366
The fifth was a ''Cornflower'',
the nickname for the class of '1 7.

73
00:09:10,527 --> 00:09:12,836
He was five months shy of 20.

74
00:09:15,367 --> 00:09:17,835
These days, everything scared him.

75
00:09:18,047 --> 00:09:19,799
French canons short-firing,

76
00:09:19,967 --> 00:09:23,357
the wind that heralded
the mustard gas attacks,

77
00:09:23,607 --> 00:09:25,598
executions to set an example.

78
00:09:26,167 --> 00:09:28,237
He hadn't been like that before,

79
00:09:28,407 --> 00:09:29,681
quite the opposite,

80
00:09:29,847 --> 00:09:33,760
braving storms as he helped
lighthouse keepers.

81
00:10:03,567 --> 00:10:06,001
And then came one shell too many.

82
00:11:07,207 --> 00:11:10,404
There you go... The winning ticket
back to your fiance.

83
00:11:10,567 --> 00:11:12,205
The ticket for a court-martial.

84
00:11:12,367 --> 00:11:15,643
Turn a blind eye, Sarge.
He's been through enough.

85
00:11:15,807 --> 00:11:17,035
They could execute him.

86
00:11:17,207 --> 00:11:18,925
- Be human for once.
- Shut up!

87
00:11:19,087 --> 00:11:20,281
Please, Sarge!

88
00:11:20,447 --> 00:11:21,243
Shut up!

89
00:11:27,607 --> 00:11:30,440
The first time
Mathilde and Manech made love,

90
00:11:31,007 --> 00:11:33,646
he fell asleep,
his hand on her breast.

91
00:11:55,847 --> 00:11:57,724
Each time his wound throbs,

92
00:11:57,887 --> 00:12:00,765
Manech feels Mathilde's heart
in his palm.

93
00:12:00,927 --> 00:12:03,316
Each beat brings her closer to him.

94
00:12:07,367 --> 00:12:10,677
lf Manech were dead,
Mathilde would know.

95
00:12:12,167 --> 00:12:13,919
Since the death notice,

96
00:12:14,087 --> 00:12:18,126
she stubbornly holds on to her
intuition, like to a flimsy wire.

97
00:12:18,647 --> 00:12:20,842
She never gets discouraged.

98
00:12:23,167 --> 00:12:25,476
And Mathilde
is of a cheerful disposition.

99
00:12:25,807 --> 00:12:30,323
lf that wire doesn't lead her
to her lover, never mind...

100
00:12:30,647 --> 00:12:32,877
she can always use it as a noose.

101
00:12:38,487 --> 00:12:42,765
ln June 1920, Mathilde received
a letter from a nun.

102
00:12:43,007 --> 00:12:46,158
A patient at the Rennes hospital
wants to see her.

103
00:12:47,207 --> 00:12:51,598
He'd met Manech in January '1 7
at the Front in the Somme.

104
00:12:57,647 --> 00:12:59,239
August 191 2.

105
00:13:00,007 --> 00:13:01,599
Handsome, wasn't l?

106
00:13:02,207 --> 00:13:03,322
lt's a De Dion,

107
00:13:04,247 --> 00:13:05,646
with direct drive.

108
00:13:06,727 --> 00:13:08,638
Please, tell me about Manech.

109
00:13:09,527 --> 00:13:11,006
ln January '1 7,

110
00:13:11,967 --> 00:13:14,606
l escorted five condemned soldiers.

111
00:13:18,367 --> 00:13:20,005
He was one of them...

112
00:13:20,247 --> 00:13:21,123
Yes.

113
00:13:22,167 --> 00:13:24,556
l was to take them
to a front-line trench.

114
00:13:31,767 --> 00:13:34,235
Gendarmes were waiting
with the prisoners

115
00:13:34,527 --> 00:13:36,677
near a bombed-out cemetery.

116
00:13:45,447 --> 00:13:47,836
What are you doing
with those German boots?

117
00:13:48,007 --> 00:13:48,917
Waiting.

118
00:13:49,207 --> 00:13:50,196
What for?

119
00:13:50,527 --> 00:13:52,597
Poincar's pardon? You'll wait!

120
00:13:53,847 --> 00:13:55,326
He'll sign it!

121
00:13:55,647 --> 00:13:57,922
l shouldn't
even have been condemned.

122
00:13:58,087 --> 00:14:00,726
l'm Corsican, not French!

123
00:14:09,487 --> 00:14:10,556
Leave him be.

124
00:14:10,807 --> 00:14:13,037
He's lost it,
but that's for the best.

125
00:14:21,087 --> 00:14:22,759
Finished, Lieutenant?

126
00:14:25,007 --> 00:14:27,077
The cold has saved that one.

127
00:14:27,287 --> 00:14:29,676
Gangrene would've got him
in summer.

128
00:14:33,367 --> 00:14:34,641
And Manech?

129
00:14:36,007 --> 00:14:37,725
Was he in pain?

130
00:14:38,647 --> 00:14:40,797
They had to cut off two fingers,

131
00:14:40,967 --> 00:14:42,764
but he wasn't suffering anymore.

132
00:14:44,807 --> 00:14:46,365
l led them to a trench,

133
00:14:46,527 --> 00:14:48,563
called ''Bingo Crpuscule''.

134
00:15:05,247 --> 00:15:06,475
Bloody hell!

135
00:15:06,927 --> 00:15:08,997
Couldn't you have lost them
on your way?

136
00:15:09,167 --> 00:15:11,556
A kick in the ass
to get rid of them!

137
00:15:12,247 --> 00:15:14,681
My orders
are to bring you these five.

138
00:15:14,847 --> 00:15:16,360
And l'll tell you my orders!

139
00:15:16,727 --> 00:15:19,560
l'm to throw these guys over the top

140
00:15:19,847 --> 00:15:21,758
and leave them to die like dogs

141
00:15:21,927 --> 00:15:23,883
between our line and the Jerries'!

142
00:15:24,047 --> 00:15:26,436
Those are my damned orders,
Sergeant!

143
00:15:28,367 --> 00:15:31,837
You see, Sergeant, with the Jerries,

144
00:15:32,007 --> 00:15:34,441
lt's a little too calm?
Let's start the fireworks

145
00:15:34,607 --> 00:15:36,359
and watch all hell let loose!

146
00:15:38,647 --> 00:15:41,400
Soup, guys!
You're lucky, it's still warm.

147
00:15:44,007 --> 00:15:45,360
Beetroot and fennel.

148
00:15:51,047 --> 00:15:53,083
What can l get for you?

149
00:15:54,447 --> 00:15:57,484
A large hot chocolate
and some bread with honey.

150
00:15:57,727 --> 00:16:00,321
l'd kill my parents to get you that!

151
00:16:01,007 --> 00:16:02,759
Do you mind, Lieutenant?

152
00:16:04,087 --> 00:16:05,645
He's an orphan!

153
00:16:05,927 --> 00:16:09,602
He'll get it. Clestin Poux
is the ''Mess Hall Marauder'',

154
00:16:10,007 --> 00:16:11,804
the ''Kitchen Raider''.

155
00:16:13,127 --> 00:16:16,324
Fifteen minutes later,
he came back with it all.

156
00:16:16,607 --> 00:16:18,245
Salted Gurande butter,

157
00:16:18,767 --> 00:16:19,916
lavender honey,

158
00:16:20,247 --> 00:16:21,236
and...

159
00:16:21,847 --> 00:16:23,758
cocoa from Nigeria!

160
00:16:27,967 --> 00:16:28,797
Grand...

161
00:16:29,447 --> 00:16:30,800
Tell me, Cornflower,

162
00:16:31,247 --> 00:16:34,205
you've no one to write to?
A fiance?

163
00:16:35,527 --> 00:16:36,596
Mathilde.

164
00:16:37,527 --> 00:16:39,119
Her name is Mathilde.

165
00:16:44,127 --> 00:16:46,880
l hear her heart beating,
like Morse code.

166
00:16:49,807 --> 00:16:50,922
We're engaged.

167
00:16:54,407 --> 00:16:58,002
Luckily, we won't have to wait
till the end of the war.

168
00:16:59,727 --> 00:17:02,958
Now l can go straight home
after the execution.

169
00:17:13,647 --> 00:17:15,877
Should l spare you the rest?

170
00:17:17,647 --> 00:17:19,524
l'm lame, not dim.

171
00:17:20,287 --> 00:17:21,686
What happened?

172
00:17:23,527 --> 00:17:25,643
We opened the barbed wire

173
00:17:26,447 --> 00:17:29,200
and equipped the five
against the cold.

174
00:17:32,847 --> 00:17:37,443
Clestin Poux gave up a red woolen
glove to protect your fianc's hand.

175
00:17:40,327 --> 00:17:41,282
Are they far?

176
00:17:41,447 --> 00:17:44,519
Too far for grenades,
too near for artillery.

177
00:17:44,687 --> 00:17:48,157
Gas is out of the question.
The gasser always gets it!

178
00:17:48,327 --> 00:17:49,476
Think they'll make it?

179
00:17:49,647 --> 00:17:53,117
lf they're not blown to bits,
they'll starve and freeze.

180
00:17:53,727 --> 00:17:55,957
Either way, it'll amuse the Jerries.

181
00:18:01,487 --> 00:18:04,718
A Corporal gave Bastoche,
the carpenter, a hug.

182
00:18:05,327 --> 00:18:06,840
lt was Corporal Gordes.

183
00:18:07,207 --> 00:18:09,482
They clearly knew each other
before the war.

184
00:18:10,207 --> 00:18:11,117
And then,

185
00:18:11,687 --> 00:18:13,359
over they went.

186
00:18:17,247 --> 00:18:19,078
- Shit...
- Shut up.

187
00:18:27,727 --> 00:18:29,445
- Shit!
- Shut up!

188
00:18:33,487 --> 00:18:34,715
September '1 4.

189
00:18:35,047 --> 00:18:36,605
150 pound weight, easy!

190
00:18:37,287 --> 00:18:39,642
And l wasn't at my best!

191
00:18:40,167 --> 00:18:41,395
But that morning,

192
00:18:42,247 --> 00:18:44,715
in January '1 7,
was Manech still alive?

193
00:18:45,287 --> 00:18:48,802
At dawn,
Favart called out their names.

194
00:18:50,687 --> 00:18:53,838
Apart from the Dordogne farmer,
they all replied.

195
00:18:54,007 --> 00:18:55,201
Bassignano!

196
00:18:55,367 --> 00:18:56,322
Sir!

197
00:18:56,487 --> 00:18:57,442
Bouquet!

198
00:18:57,607 --> 00:18:58,960
What now?

199
00:18:59,567 --> 00:19:00,841
Langonnet!

200
00:19:01,487 --> 00:19:02,966
Yeah, still here!

201
00:19:03,167 --> 00:19:05,886
The Cornflower,
hide yourself better.

202
00:19:06,447 --> 00:19:07,766
Notre Dame!

203
00:19:12,447 --> 00:19:13,516
That's all l know.

204
00:19:16,407 --> 00:19:18,398
l wrote up my report
with a heavy heart.

205
00:19:24,247 --> 00:19:27,205
About time, Esperanza! The Brits
are replacing us, we're off.

206
00:19:27,367 --> 00:19:29,278
So, Bingo-thingy?

207
00:19:29,927 --> 00:19:30,837
What's that?

208
00:19:31,007 --> 00:19:34,283
The condemned prisoners' list,
signed by Capt. Favourier.

209
00:19:34,447 --> 00:19:35,800
Give it to me.

210
00:19:46,487 --> 00:19:49,081
Don't just stand there like that.
This isn't Pompeii!

211
00:19:49,527 --> 00:19:52,246
You've been promoted.
You're off to the Vosges.

212
00:19:52,407 --> 00:19:53,886
Even so, Sir,

213
00:19:54,127 --> 00:19:56,925
this expedition is going to be
hard to swallow.

214
00:19:57,087 --> 00:19:58,042
Lucky you.

215
00:19:58,207 --> 00:20:01,040
Where you're going, there's
mustard gas and throat lozenges.

216
00:20:01,207 --> 00:20:02,720
The famous Vosges sweets.

217
00:20:02,887 --> 00:20:03,763
Dismissed!

218
00:20:04,127 --> 00:20:07,164
A few months later,
l was wounded, in the Somme.

219
00:20:07,847 --> 00:20:10,919
l ended up in the same ambulance
as Chardolot,

220
00:20:11,487 --> 00:20:13,682
a corporal from Bingo Crpuscule.

221
00:20:14,847 --> 00:20:17,077
But he only had
a few days left to live.

222
00:20:21,887 --> 00:20:23,445
lt's me. Esperanza.

223
00:20:24,127 --> 00:20:25,526
Bingo Crpuscule, remember?

224
00:20:26,927 --> 00:20:28,804
Sorry, l don't recognize you.

225
00:20:29,007 --> 00:20:32,079
The five thrown over
into no-man's-land,

226
00:20:32,847 --> 00:20:34,200
what happened to them?

227
00:20:34,607 --> 00:20:35,642
What do you think?

228
00:20:37,007 --> 00:20:38,235
No one made it.

229
00:20:38,727 --> 00:20:41,525
Your conscience bothering you,
Esperanza?

230
00:20:41,887 --> 00:20:43,957
You should've stuck around.

231
00:20:45,767 --> 00:20:47,564
You'd have seen capital Ms,

232
00:20:47,727 --> 00:20:50,924
underwear being waved
and a flying albatross.

233
00:20:52,327 --> 00:20:54,477
You're delirious with fever!

234
00:20:55,247 --> 00:20:59,957
We sent over five men
and recovered five stiffs.

235
00:21:00,287 --> 00:21:01,322
Conclusion...

236
00:21:04,927 --> 00:21:08,886
My eyes are gone but l can imagine
your expression and l like it.

237
00:21:10,567 --> 00:21:13,764
He really spoke of capital Ms
and an albatross?

238
00:21:15,487 --> 00:21:16,840
And underwear.

239
00:21:18,527 --> 00:21:19,926
Here you go, Miss.

240
00:21:20,087 --> 00:21:20,837
ln here

241
00:21:21,007 --> 00:21:25,205
are the prisoners' belongings
l was to return to their families.

242
00:21:26,207 --> 00:21:28,277
My health's prevented it.

243
00:21:29,607 --> 00:21:32,599
That's the letter
the Dordogne farmer, Notre Dame,

244
00:21:32,767 --> 00:21:33,483
wrote to his wife.

245
00:21:33,847 --> 00:21:36,486
l sent the original
just after Bingo.

246
00:21:37,567 --> 00:21:39,797
You're here
because of the mustard gas?

247
00:21:40,767 --> 00:21:43,201
Not even. Damned Spanish flu!

248
00:21:44,207 --> 00:21:47,882
Death moves in mysterious ways.

249
00:21:53,487 --> 00:21:55,717
lf you can't cry, try talking.

250
00:21:58,567 --> 00:22:00,319
lf you can't talk, say nothing.

251
00:22:01,927 --> 00:22:05,681
But sometimes,
talking can bring on the tears.

252
00:22:05,847 --> 00:22:07,917
Tears say what you can't say,

253
00:22:08,087 --> 00:22:09,759
if you get my drift?

254
00:22:12,847 --> 00:22:15,486
Otherwise,
you can just keep that sour-face!

255
00:22:46,087 --> 00:22:48,442
Little Louis,
tell Vro l'm thinking of her.

256
00:22:48,607 --> 00:22:50,563
Shame she won't talk to me.

257
00:22:50,727 --> 00:22:52,877
Saw Biscuit, we patched things up.

258
00:22:53,047 --> 00:22:54,844
Adieu, my friend. Bastoche.

259
00:22:59,407 --> 00:23:03,559
''Benoit Notre Dame, number 1818.
l won't be writing for a long time.''

260
